# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guile-scheme
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] In computer science, a **continuation** is an abstract representation of the control state of a computer program.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations are useful for encoding other control mechanisms in programming languages such as exceptions, generators, coroutines, and so on.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The "**current continuation**" or "continuation of the computation step" is the continuation that, from the perspective of running code, would be derived from the current point in a program's execution.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The term *continuations* can also be used to refer to **first-class continuations**, which are constructs that give a programming language the ability to save the execution state at any point and return to that point at a later point in the program, possibly multiple times.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The earliest description of continuations was made by Adriaan van Wijngaarden in September 1964.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Wijngaarden spoke at the IFIP Working Conference on Formal Language Description Languages held in Baden bei Wien, Austria.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] As part of a formulation for an Algol 60 preprocessor, he called for a transformation of proper procedures into continuation-passing style, though he did not use this name, and his intention was to simplify a program and thus make its result more clear.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Reynolds brought the term *continuation* into prominence in their work in the field of denotational semantics that makes extensive use of continuations to allow sequential programs to be analysed in terms of functional programming semantics.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Steve Russell invented the continuation in his second Lisp implementation for the IBM 704, though he did not name it.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Reynolds (1993) gives a complete history of the discovery of continuations.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] First-class continuations are a language's ability to completely control the execution order of instructions.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] They can be used to jump to a function that produced the call to the current function, or to a function that has previously exited.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] One can think of a first-class continuation as saving the *execution* state of the program.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] True first-class continuations do not save program data – unlike a process image – only the execution context.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Scheme was the first full production system providing first "catch" and then call/cc.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations are also used in models of computation including denotational semantics, the actor model, process calculi, and lambda calculus.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] These models rely on programmers or semantics engineers to write mathematical functions in the so-called continuation-passing style.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] This means that each function consumes a function that represents the rest of the computation relative to this function call.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] To return a value, the function calls this "continuation function" with a return value; to abort the computation it returns a value.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Functional programmers who write their programs in continuation-passing style gain the expressive power to manipulate the flow of control in arbitrary ways.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The cost is that they must maintain the invariants of control and continuations by hand, which can be a highly complex undertaking (but see 'continuation-passing style' below).
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations simplify and clarify the implementation of several common design patterns, including coroutines/green threads and exception handling, by providing the basic, low-level primitive which unifies these seemingly unconnected patterns.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations can provide elegant solutions to some difficult high-level problems, like programming a web server that supports multiple pages, accessed by the use of the forward and back buttons and by following links.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The Smalltalk Seaside web framework uses continuations to great effect, allowing one to program the web server in procedural style, by switching continuations when switching pages.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] More complex constructs for which *"continuations provide an elegant description"* also exist.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] For example, in C, longjmp can be used to jump from the middle of one function to another, provided the second function lies deeper in the stack (if it is waiting for the first function to return, possibly among others).
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Other more complex examples include coroutines in Simula 67, Lua, and Perl; tasklets in Stackless Python; generators in Icon and Python; continuations in Scala (starting in 2.8); fibers in Ruby (starting in 1.9.1); the backtracking mechanism in Prolog; monads in functional programming; and threads.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] For a gentler introduction to this mechanism, see call-with-current-continuation.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] This example shows a possible usage of continuations to implement coroutines as separate threads.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] A program must allocate space in memory for the variables its functions use.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Most programming languages use a call stack for storing the variables needed because it allows for fast and simple allocating and automatic deallocation of memory.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Other programming languages use a heap for this, which allows for flexibility at a higher cost for allocating and deallocating memory.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Both of these implementations have benefits and drawbacks in the context of continuations.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] In any language which supports closures and proper tail calls, it is possible to write programs in continuation-passing style and manually implement call/cc.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] (In continuation-passing style, call/cc becomes a simple function that can be written with lambda.) This is a particularly common strategy in Haskell, where it is easy to construct a "continuation-passing monad" (for example, the `Cont` monad and `ContT` monad transformer in the `mtl` library).
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The support for proper tail calls is needed because in continuation-passing style no function ever returns; *all* calls are tail calls.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] One area that has seen practical use of continuations is in Web programming.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The use of continuations shields the programmer from the stateless nature of the HTTP protocol.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] In the traditional model of web programming, the lack of state is reflected in the program's structure, leading to code constructed around a model that lends itself very poorly to expressing computational problems.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Thus continuations enable code that has the useful properties associated with inversion of control, while avoiding its problems.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] "Inverting back the inversion of control or, Continuations versus page-centric programming" is a paper that provides a good introduction to continuations applied to web programming.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Support for continuations varies widely.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] A programming language supports *re-invocable* continuations if a continuation may be invoked repeatedly (even after it has already returned).
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Re-invocable continuations were introduced by Peter J.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Landin using his **J** (for Jump) operator that could transfer the flow of control back into the middle of a procedure invocation.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Re-invocable continuations have also been called "re-entrant" in the Racket language.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] However this use of the term "re-entrant" can be easily confused with its use in discussions of multithreading.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] A more limited kind is the *escape continuation* that may be used to escape the current context to a surrounding one.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Many languages which do not explicitly support continuations support exception handling, which is equivalent to escape continuations and can be used for the same purposes.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] C's `setjmp/longjmp` are also equivalent: they can only be used to unwind the stack.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Escape continuations can also be used to implement tail call elimination.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] One generalization of continuations are delimited continuations.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuation operators like `call/cc` capture the *entire* remaining computation at a given point in the program and provide no way of delimiting this capture.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Delimited continuation operators address this by providing two separate control mechanisms: a *prompt* that delimits a continuation operation and a *reification* operator such as `shift` or `control`.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations captured using delimited operators thus only represent a slice of the program context.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] Continuations are the functional expression of the GOTO statement, and the same caveats apply.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] While they are a sensible option in some special cases such as web programming, use of continuations can result in code that is difficult to follow.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] In fact, the esoteric programming language Unlambda includes call-with-current-continuation as one of its features solely because expressions involving it "tend to be hopelessly difficult to track down".
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The external links below illustrate the concept in more detail.
[src:guile-scheme/continuation] The extent to which continuations can be used to explain other general phenomena in natural language is a topic of current research.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:guile-scheme/extension-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Guile is used in many programs under the GNU project umbrella (GDB, Make, Guix, GNU TeXmacs, GnuCash, LilyPond, Lepton-EDA...) but it also sees use outside of that, for example in Google's schism.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Guile Scheme is a general-purpose, high-level programming language whose flexibility allows expressing concepts in fewer lines of code than would be possible in languages such as C.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] For example, its hygienic macro system allows adding domain specific syntax-elements without modifying Guile.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Guile implements the Scheme standard R5RS, most of R6RS and R7RS, several Scheme Requests for Implementation (SRFI), and many extensions of its own.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] The core idea of Guile Scheme is that "the developer implements critical algorithms and data structures in C or C++ and exports the functions and types for use by interpreted code.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Guile programs can use facilities from SLIB, the portable Scheme library.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] When using continuations with call/cc, a requirement of the Scheme standard, Guile copies the execution stack into the heap and back.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Its manual suggests using delimited continuations instead, because they have a more efficient implementation.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Because foreign code may have pointers to Scheme objects, Guile uses the conservative Boehm–Demers–Weiser (BDW) garbage collector.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] The Guile manual gives details of the inception and early history of the language.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] After the success of Emacs in the free software community, as a highly extensible and customizable application via its extension (and partly implementation) language Emacs Lisp, the community began to consider how this design strategy could apply to the rest of the GNU system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Tom Lord initially began work on an embeddable language runtime named the GNU Extension Language (GEL), which was based on Aubrey Jaffer's Scheme implementation SCM (which in turn was based on George Carrette's SIOD).
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Lord convinced Richard Stallman to make GEL the official extension language of the GNU project, based on the argument that Scheme was a cleaner Lisp dialect than Emacs Lisp, and that GEL could evolve to implement other languages on the same runtime, namely Emacs Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] After Lord discovered GEL had a naming conflict with another programming language, he solicited suggestions for a new name.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] From several contributions in several Usenet newsgroups, Lord controversially chose Guile from a suggestion by Lee Thomas.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] During the development of Guile (then GEL) and before its public release, the extension language Tcl was gaining popularity and being pushed as a universal extension language.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Stallman saw Tcl as being underpowered as an extension language, and posted a criticism to the comp.lang.tcl newsgroup, which initiated a flamewar known as the "Tcl War".
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Since the public announcement of the Guile project coincided with the Tcl debate, it has become a common misconception that Guile began as a reaction to this.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] One of the goals of Guile is to allow other languages to be used alongside Scheme, such that Guile would effectively be a language-neutral runtime environment.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Various attempts at this have been made in past versions: a dialect of Scheme essentially differing only in its C-like syntax, a translation of Emacs Lisp, a Tcl converter motivated by tkWWW, and something roughly resembling the language Logo.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] With version 2.0, the project successfully transitioned to a *compiler tower* approach, allowing the definition of compilers from one language to another, typically from a higher-level one to a lower-level intermediate representation, and eventually virtual machine bytecode or native machine code.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] On 16 Mar 2017, Guile 2.2.0 was released with a new optimizing compiler and high-performance register virtual machine.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] According to the release announcement by Andy Wingo, real-world programs often showed a speedup of 30% or more with Guile 2.2 when compared to the previous 2.0 series.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Guile 2.2.0 also lowered memory usage, sped up the "eval" interpreter, provided better support for multi-core programming, and removed any fixed limit on recursive function calls.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] It also supported the creation of user-space concurrency facilities that multiplex millions of concurrent lightweight "fibers" and provided a complete Emacs-compatible Elisp implementation, implementing all of Elisp's features and quirks in the same way as Emacs.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] On 16 January 2020, Guile 3.0.0 was released with just-in-time (JIT) native code generation for much greater performance.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Compared to 2.2, microbenchmark performance is around twice as good on the whole, while some individual benchmarks are up to 32 times as fast.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] It also featured support for interleaved definitions and expressions in lexical contexts, native support for structured exceptions, better support for the R6RS and R7RS Scheme standards and many optimizations.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] There have been several past unfinished attempts to replace or supplement the Emacs Lisp extension language with Guile, parallel to the efforts of supporting other languages in Guile.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] With version 2.0 of Guile, a new attempt at implementing Elisp on the Guile compiler tower and replacing Emacs's Elisp implementation with that of libguile has begun and made significant progress through Google Summer of Code projects.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] As of October 2014, the implementation had reached a stage where Guile Emacs is able to reliably run most Emacs Lisp code.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] Other concerns raised by the Emacs community include the relative sizes of the Emacs and Guile communities, and whether it would cause splitting in the community if Emacs were extensible in programming languages other than Emacs Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] At EmacsConf 2024, the relaunch of Guile-Emacs was announced.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-guile] GNU make can be built with support for GNU Guile as an embedded extension language.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The **GNU Project** (/ɡnuː/ ⓘ *GNOO*) is a free software, mass collaboration project announced by Richard Stallman on September 27, 1983.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Its goal is to provide computer users freedom and control in their use of their computers and computing devices by developing and publishing software collaboratively that grants everyone the right to freely run, copy, distribute, study, and modify it.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] GNU software grants these rights in its license.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In order to ensure that the *entire* software of a computer grants its users all rights (use, share, study, modify), even the most fundamental and important parts, the operating system and all of its utility programs, need to be free software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Stallman decided to call this operating system *GNU* (a recursive acronym meaning "*GNU's not Unix!*"), basing its design on that of Unix, a proprietary operating system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] According to its manifesto, the founding goal of the project was to build a free operating system, and if possible, "everything useful that normally comes with a Unix system so that one could get along without any software that is not free." Development was initiated in January 1984.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In 1991, the Linux kernel appeared, developed outside the GNU Project by Linus Torvalds, and in December 1992, it was made available under version 2 of the GNU General Public License.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Combined with the operating system utilities already developed by the GNU Project, it allowed for the first operating system that was free software, commonly known as Linux.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The project's current work includes software development, awareness building, political campaigning, and sharing of new material.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In the late 1970s, Richard Stallman had an issue with a new printer installed in the MIT AI Lab, where he worked at the time, which ran proprietary firmware.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Richard Stallman was frustrated that he could not receive a copy of the printer software and edit the code to solve his problem.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] This early experience made him realize limits of non-free software are a social issue.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Richard Stallman announced his intent to start coding the GNU Project in a Usenet message in September 1983.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Despite never having used Unix prior, Stallman felt that it was the most appropriate system design to use as a basis for the GNU Project, as it was portable and "fairly clean".
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] When the GNU Project first started it had an Emacs text editor with Lisp for writing editor commands, a source level debugger, a yacc-compatible parser generator, and a linker.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU system required its own C compiler and tools to be free software, so these also had to be developed.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] By June 1987, the project had accumulated and developed free software for an assembler, an almost finished portable optimizing C compiler (GCC), an editor (GNU Emacs), and various Unix utilities (such as `ls`, `grep`, `awk`, `make` and `ld`).
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Richard Stallman also mentioned in the GNU manifesto that an initial kernel exists for the GNU operating system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] That kernel was soon revealed to be the TRIX kernel.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Developers attempted to use TRIX as the base of the GNU kernel, but abandoned the effort in favour of GNU Mach.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Once the kernel and the compiler were finished, GNU was able to be used for program development.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The main goal was to create many other applications to be like the Unix system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] GNU was able to run Unix programs, but was not identical to it.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] GNU incorporated longer file names, file version numbers, and a crash-proof file system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Manifesto was written to gain support and participation from others for the project.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Programmers were encouraged to take part in any aspect of the project that interested them.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] People could donate funds, computer parts, or even their own time to write code and programs for the project.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The origins and development of most aspects of the GNU Project (and free software in general) are shared in a detailed narrative in the Emacs help system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] (C-h g runs the Emacs editor command describe-gnu-project.) It is the same detailed history as at their web site.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Manifesto was written by Richard Stallman to gain support and participation in the GNU Project.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] To implement these freedoms, users needed full access to the source code.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] To ensure code remained free and provide it to the public, Stallman created the GNU General Public License (GPL), which allowed software and the future generations of code derived from it to remain free for public use.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Although most of the GNU Project's output is technical in nature, it was launched as a social, ethical, and political initiative.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] As well as producing software and licenses, the GNU Project has published a number of writings, the majority of which were authored by Richard Stallman.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Project uses software that is free for users to copy, edit, and distribute.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] It is free in the sense that users can change the software to fit individual needs.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The way programmers obtain the free software depends on where they get it.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The software could be provided to the programmer from friends or over the Internet, or the company a programmer works for may purchase the software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Proceeds from Free Software Foundation associate members, purchases, and donations support the GNU Project.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Project recommends that contributors assign the copyright for GNU packages to the Free Software Foundation, though the Free Software Foundation considers it acceptable to release small changes to an existing project to the public domain.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] However, this is not required; package maintainers may retain copyright to the GNU packages they maintain, though since only the copyright holder may enforce the license used (such as the GNU GPL), the copyright holder in this case enforces it rather than the Free Software Foundation.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] For the development of needed software, Stallman wrote a license called the GNU General Public License (first called Emacs General Public License), with the goal to guarantee users freedom to share and change free software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Stallman wrote this license after his experience with James Gosling and a program called UniPress, over a controversy around software code use in the GNU Emacs program.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] For most of the 80s, each GNU package had its own license: the Emacs General Public License, the GCC General Public License, etc.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In 1989, FSF published a single license they could use for all their software, and which could be used by non-GNU projects: the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] This license is now used by most of GNU software, as well as a large number of free software programs that are not part of the GNU Project; it also historically has been the most commonly used free software license (though recently challenged by the MIT license).
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] It gives all recipients of a program the right to run, copy, modify and distribute it, while forbidding them from imposing further restrictions on any copies they distribute.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] This idea is often referred to as copyleft.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In 1991, the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), then known as the Library General Public License, was written for the GNU C Library to allow it to be linked with proprietary software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] 1991 also saw the release of version 2 of the GNU GPL.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Free Documentation License (FDL), for documentation, followed in 2000.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GPL and LGPL were revised to version 3 in 2007, adding clauses to protect users against hardware restrictions that prevent users from running modified software on their own devices.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Besides GNU's packages, the GNU Project's licenses can and are used by many unrelated projects, such as the Linux kernel, often used with GNU software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] A majority of free software such as the X Window System, is licensed under permissive free software licenses.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Copyleft licenses help maintain free use of this software among other programmers.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Copyleft gives everyone the legal right to use, edit, and redistribute programs or programs' code as long as the distribution terms do not change.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] As a result, any user who obtains the software legally has the same freedoms as the rest of its users do.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Project and the Free Software Foundation sometimes differentiate between "strong" and "weak" copyleft licenses.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] "Weak" copyleft programs typically allow distributors to link them together with non-free programs, while "strong" copyleft strictly forbids this practice.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Most of the GNU Project's output is released under a strong copyleft, although some is released under a weak copyleft or a lax, push-over free software license.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The first goal of the GNU Project was to create a whole free-software operating system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Because UNIX was already widespread and ran on more powerful machines, compared to contemporary CP/M or MS-DOS machines of time, it was decided it would be a Unix-like operating system.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Richard Stallman later commented that he considered MS-DOS "a toy".
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] By 1992, the GNU Project had completed all of the major operating system utilities, but had not completed their proposed operating system kernel, GNU Hurd.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] With the release of the Linux kernel for the first time under the GPLv2 with version 0.12 in 1992--the project was started independently by Linus Torvalds in 1991 but not under GPL--it was possible to run an operating system composed completely of free software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Though the Linux kernel is not part of the GNU Project, it was developed using GCC and other GNU programming tools and was released as free software under the GNU General Public License.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Most compilation of the Linux kernel is still done with GNU toolchains, but it is currently possible to use the Clang compiler and the LLVM toolchain for compilation.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] As of present, the GNU Project has not released a version of GNU/Hurd that is suitable for production environments since the commencement of the GNU/Hurd project over 35 years ago.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNU Free System Distribution Guidelines (GNU FSDG) is a system distribution commitment that explains how an installable system distribution (such as a Linux distribution) qualifies as free (libre), and helps distribution developers make their distributions qualify.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The list mostly describes distributions that are a combination of GNU packages with a Linux-libre kernel (a modified Linux kernel that removes binary blobs, obfuscated code, and portions of code under proprietary licenses) and consist only of free software (eschewing proprietary software entirely).
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Distributions that have adopted the GNU FSDG include Dragora GNU/Linux-Libre, GNU Guix System, Hyperbola GNU/Linux-libre, Parabola GNU/Linux-libre, Trisquel GNU/Linux, PureOS, and a few others.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In 2022, Debian was close to becoming a FSF endorsed distro but it had another repository on its servers with non-free packages, therefore it did not become FSF endorsed.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] And in 2022 Debian 12 added an option in the installer for non-free hardware to work by running non-free code.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The Fedora Project's distribution license guidelines were used as a basis for the FSDG.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The Fedora Project's own guidelines, however, currently do not follow the FSDG, and thus the GNU Project does not consider Fedora to be a fully free (libre) GNU/Linux distribution.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] From the mid-1990s onward, with many companies investing in free software development, the Free Software Foundation redirected its funds toward the legal and political support of free software development.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Software development from that point on focused on maintaining existing projects, and starting new projects only when there was an acute threat to the free software community.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] One of the most notable projects of the GNU Project is the GNU Compiler Collection, whose components have been adopted as the standard compiler system on many Unix-like systems.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The copyright of most works by the GNU Project is owned by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The GNOME desktop effort was launched by the GNU Project because another desktop system, KDE, was becoming popular, but required users to install Qt, which was then proprietary software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] To prevent people from being tempted to install KDE and Qt, the GNU Project simultaneously launched two projects.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] This was an attempt to make a free software replacement for Qt.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Had this project been successful, the perceived problem with the KDE would have been solved.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The second project was GNOME, which tackled the same issue from a different angle.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] It aimed to make a replacement for KDE that had no dependencies on proprietary software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] The Harmony project did not make much progress, but GNOME developed very well.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] Eventually, the proprietary component that KDE depended on (Qt) was released as free software.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] GNOME has since dissociated itself from the GNU Project and the Free Software Foundation, and is now independently managed by the GNOME Project.
[src:guile-scheme/gnu-project] In 2001, the GNU Project received the USENIX Lifetime Achievement Award for "the ubiquity, breadth, and quality of its freely available redistributable and modifiable software, which has enabled a generation of research and commercial development".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:guile-scheme/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The term usually refers to programming interfaces similar to the classic Lisp machine interactive environment or to Common Lisp with the SLIME development environment.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Common examples include command-line shells and similar environments for programming languages, and the technique is very characteristic of scripting languages, even though their characteristics can vary greatly.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The expression *READ-EVAL-PRINT cycle* is used by L.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Peter Deutsch and Edmund Berkeley for a 1964 implementation of Lisp on the PDP-1.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Just one month later, Project Mac published a report by Joseph Weizenbaum (the creator of ELIZA, the world's first chatbot) describing a REPL-based language, called OPL-1, implemented in his Fortran-SLIP language on the Compatible Time Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The 1974 Maclisp reference manual by David A.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Moon attests "Read-eval-print loop" on page 89, but does not use the acronym REPL.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Since at least the 1980s, the abbreviations *REP Loop* and *REPL* are attested in the context of Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] In a REPL, the user enters one or more expressions (rather than an entire compilation unit) and the REPL evaluates them and displays the results.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The development environment then returns to the read state, creating a loop, which terminates when the program is closed.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] REPLs facilitate exploratory programming and debugging because the programmer can inspect the printed result before deciding what expression to provide for the next read.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The read–eval–print loop involves the programmer more frequently than the classic edit–compile–run–debug cycle.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Because the *print* function outputs in the same textual format that the *read* function uses for input, most results are printed in a form that could be copied and pasted back into the REPL.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] However, it is sometimes necessary to print representations of elements that cannot sensibly be read back in, such as a socket handle or a complex class instance.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] In these cases, there must exist a syntax for unreadable objects.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] In Python, it is the `<__module__.class instance>` notation, and in Common Lisp, the `#<whatever>` form.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The REPL of CLIM, SLIME, and the Symbolics Lisp Machine can also read back unreadable objects.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] They record for each output which object was printed.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Later when the code is read back, the object will be retrieved from the printed output.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] REPLs can be created to support any text-based language.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] REPL support for compiled languages is usually achieved by implementing an interpreter on top of a virtual machine which provides an interface to the compiler.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] For example, starting with JDK 9, Java included JShell as a command-line interface to the language.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Various other languages have third-party tools available for download that provide similar shell interaction with the language, although the features can vary greatly.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] As a shell, a REPL environment allows users to access relevant features of an operating system in addition to providing access to programming capabilities.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The most common use for REPLs outside of operating system shells is for interactive prototyping.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Other uses include mathematical calculation, creating documents that integrate scientific analysis (e.g.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] IPython), interactive software maintenance, benchmarking, and algorithm exploration.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] where `read` waits for user input and `eval` evaluates it.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] `print` prints the result, and `loop` loops indefinitely.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] You can enter `(+ 1 1)` and stop the loop with `C-c`.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] Developers of Lisp applications typically do *not* write or copy-paste code to a REPL.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] They use the REPL for quick tests, for debugging and to explore a running system.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] They write their application in a source file under version control, they use commands or keyboard shortcuts to compile their code interactively.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The Lisp process is running and connected to their editor, and it compiles new code "on the fly", without restarting.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] In Common Lisp, developers typically compile the current function they are working on.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] They can also compile a whole file, or compile a whole project.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] When a function is compiled, they may get type warnings (specially with the SBCL implementation), and they can invoke the newly created function from the REPL.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] If an error occurs, they are given an interactive debugger.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] This process of compiling one single function and testing it on the REPL is very fast in comparison to other processes.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] The cycle of writing a new function, compiling it and testing is very short, and interactive, making it suitable for development.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] It also means that the application state is not lost during development.
[src:guile-scheme/read-eval-print-loop] It is only when they choose to do so that they run or compile all the application from scratch.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme language is standardized in the official Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard and a *de facto* standard named the *Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme* (R*n*RS).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A widely implemented standard is R5RS (1998).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The most recently ratified standard of Scheme is "R7RS-small" (2013).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The more expansive and modular R6RS was ratified in 2007.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both trace their descent from R5RS; the timeline below reflects the chronological order of ratification.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme started in the 1970s as an attempt to understand Carl Hewitt's Actor model, for which purpose Steele and Sussman wrote a "tiny Lisp interpreter" using Maclisp and then "added mechanisms for creating actors and sending messages".
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme was originally called "Schemer", in the tradition of other Lisp-derived languages such as Planner or *Conniver*.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The current name resulted from the authors' use of the ITS operating system, which limited filenames to two components of at most six characters each.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently, "Schemer" is commonly used to refer to a Scheme programmer.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new language standardization process began at the 2003 Scheme workshop, with the goal of producing an R6RS standard in 2006.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This process broke with the earlier R*n*RS approach of unanimity.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS features a standard module system, allowing a split between the core language and libraries.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Several drafts of the R6RS specification were released, the final version being R5.97RS.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A successful vote resulted in ratifying the new standard, announced on August 28, 2007.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently the newest releases of various Scheme implementations support the R6RS standard.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is a portable reference implementation of the proposed implicitly phased libraries for R6RS, called psyntax, which loads and bootstraps itself properly on various older Scheme implementations.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A feature of R6RS is the record-type descriptor (RTD).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When an RTD is created and used, the record type representation can show the memory layout.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It also calculated object field bit mask and mutable Scheme object field bit masks, and helped the garbage collector know what to do with the fields without traversing the whole fields list that are saved in the RTD.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] RTD allows users to expand the basic RTD to create a new record system.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS introduces numerous significant changes to the language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The source code is now specified in Unicode, and a large subset of Unicode characters may now appear in Scheme symbols and identifiers, and there are other minor changes to the lexical rules.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Character data is also now specified in Unicode.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many standard procedures have been moved to the new standard libraries, which themselves form a large expansion of the standard, containing procedures and syntactic forms that were formerly not part of the standard.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new module system has been introduced, and systems for exception handling are now standardized.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Syntax-rules has been replaced with a more expressive syntactic abstraction facility (syntax-case) which allows the use of all of Scheme at macro expansion time.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Compliant implementations are now *required* to support Scheme's full numeric tower, and the semantics of numbers have been expanded, mainly in the direction of support for the IEEE 754 standard for floating point numerical representation.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard has caused controversy because some see it as a departure from the minimalist philosophy.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Two working groups were created to work on these two new versions of Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme Reports Process site has links to the working groups' charters, public discussions and issue tracking system.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The ninth draft of R7RS (small language) was made available on April 15, 2013.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A vote ratifying this draft closed on May 20, 2013, and the final report has been available since August 6, 2013, describing "the 'small' language of that effort: therefore it cannot be considered in isolation as the successor to R6RS".
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is primarily a functional programming language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It shares many characteristics with other members of the Lisp programming language family.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's very simple syntax is based on s-expressions, parenthesized lists in which a prefix operator is followed by its arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs thus consist of sequences of nested lists.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lists are also the main data structure in Scheme, leading to a close equivalence between source code and data formats (homoiconicity).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs can easily create and evaluate pieces of Scheme code dynamically.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reliance on lists as data structures is shared by all Lisp dialects.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits a rich set of list-processing primitives such as `cons`, `car` and `cdr` from its Lisp progenitors.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme uses strictly but dynamically typed variables and supports first class procedures.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus, procedures can be assigned as values to variables or passed as arguments to procedures.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This section concentrates mainly on innovative features of the language, including those features that distinguish Scheme from other Lisps.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Unless stated otherwise, descriptions of features relate to the R5RS standard.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In examples provided in this section, the notation "===> result" is used to indicate the result of evaluating the expression on the immediately preceding line.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is the same convention used in R5RS.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is a very simple language, much easier to implement than many other languages of comparable expressive power.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This ease is attributable to the use of lambda calculus to derive much of the syntax of the language from more primitive forms.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For instance of the 23 s-expression-based syntactic constructs defined in the R5RS Scheme standard, 14 are classed as derived or library forms, which can be written as macros involving more fundamental forms, principally lambda.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] : define, lambda, quote, if, define-syntax, let-syntax, letrec-syntax, syntax-rules, set!
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example: a macro to implement `let` as an expression using `lambda` to perform the variable bindings.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus using `let` as defined above a Scheme implementation would rewrite "`(let ((a 1)(b 2)) (+ b a))`" as "`((lambda (a b) (+ b a)) 1 2)`", which reduces implementation's task to that of coding procedure instantiations.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In 1998, Sussman and Steele remarked that the minimalism of Scheme was not a conscious design goal, but rather the unintended outcome of the design process.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like most modern programming languages and unlike earlier Lisps such as Maclisp, Scheme is lexically scoped: all possible variable bindings in a program unit can be analyzed by reading the text of the program unit without considering the contexts in which it may be called.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This contrasts with dynamic scoping which was characteristic of early Lisp dialects, because of the processing costs associated with the primitive textual substitution methods used to implement lexical scoping algorithms in compilers and interpreters of the day.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In those Lisps, it was fully possible for a reference to a free variable inside a procedure to refer to quite distinct bindings external to the procedure, depending on the context of the call.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The impetus to incorporate lexical scoping, which was an unusual scoping model in the early 1970s, into their new version of Lisp, came from Sussman's studies of ALGOL.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] He suggested that ALGOL-like lexical scoping mechanisms would help to realize their initial goal of implementing Carl Hewitt's Actor model in Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alonzo Church's mathematical notation, the lambda calculus, has inspired Lisp's use of "lambda" as a keyword for introducing a procedure, as well as influencing the development of functional programming techniques involving the use of higher-order functions in Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] But early Lisps were not suitable expressions of the lambda calculus because of their treatment of free variables.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A formal lambda system has axioms and a complete calculation rule.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It is helpful for the analysis using mathematical logic and tools.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In this system, calculation can be seen as a directional deduction.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The syntax of lambda calculus follows the recursive expressions from x, y, z, ...,parentheses, spaces, the period and the symbol λ.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The function of lambda calculation includes: First, serve as a starting point of powerful mathematical logic.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Second, it can reduce the requirement of programmers to consider the implementation details, because it can be used to imitate machine evaluation.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Finally, the lambda calculation created a substantial meta-theory.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introduction of lexical scope resolved the problem by making an equivalence between some forms of lambda notation and their practical expression in a working programming language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They introduced continuation-passing style along with their first description of Scheme in the first of the Lambda Papers, and in subsequent papers, they proceeded to demonstrate the raw power of this practical use of lambda calculus.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits its block structure from earlier block structured languages, particularly ALGOL.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, blocks are implemented by three *binding constructs*: `let`, `let*` and `letrec`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Blocks can be nested to create arbitrarily complex block structures according to the need of the programmer.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The use of block structuring to create local bindings alleviates the risk of namespace collision that can otherwise occur.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The other variant, `letrec`, is designed to enable mutually recursive procedures to be bound to one another.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] All procedures bound in a single `letrec` may refer to one another by name, as well as to values of variables defined earlier in the same `letrec`, but they may not refer to *values* defined later in the same `letrec`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A variant of `let`, the "named let" form, has an identifier after the `let` keyword.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This binds the let variables to the argument of a procedure whose name is the given identifier and whose body is the body of the let form.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The body may be repeated as desired by calling the procedure.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The named let is widely used to implement iteration.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like any procedure in Scheme, the procedure created in the named let is a first-class object.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme has an iteration construct, `do`, but it is more idiomatic in Scheme to use tail recursion to express iteration.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Standard-conforming Scheme implementations are required to optimize tail calls so as to support an unbounded number of active tail calls (R5RS sec.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 3.5)—a property the Scheme report describes as *proper tail recursion*—making it safe for Scheme programmers to write iterative algorithms using recursive structures, which are sometimes more intuitive.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Tail recursive procedures and the *named `let`* form provide support for iteration using tail recursion.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations in Scheme are first-class objects.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme provides the procedure `call-with-current-continuation` (also known as `call/cc`) to capture the current continuation by packing it up as an escape procedure bound to a formal argument in a procedure provided by the programmer.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.4) First-class continuations enable the programmer to create non-local control constructs such as iterators, coroutines, and backtracking.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations can be used to emulate the behavior of return statements in imperative programming languages.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following function `find-first`, given function `func` and list `lst`, returns the first element `x` in `lst` such that `(func x)` returns true.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following example, a traditional programmer's puzzle, shows that Scheme can handle continuations as first-class objects, binding them to variables and passing them as arguments to procedures.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast to Common Lisp, all data and procedures in Scheme share a common namespace, whereas in Common Lisp functions and data have separate namespaces making it possible for a function and a variable to have the same name, and requiring special notation for referring to a function as a value.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is sometimes known as the "Lisp-1 vs.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lisp-2" distinction, referring to the unified namespace of Scheme and the separate namespaces of Common Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, the same primitives that are used to manipulate and bind data can be used to bind procedures.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is no equivalent of Common Lisp's `defun` and `#'` primitives.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This subsection documents design decisions that have been taken over the years which have given Scheme a particular character, but are not the direct outcomes of the original design.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme specifies a comparatively full set of numerical datatypes including complex and rational types, which is known in Scheme as the numerical tower (R5RS sec.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard treats these as abstractions, and does not commit the implementor to any particular internal representations.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Numbers may have the quality of exactness.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] An exact number can only be produced by a sequence of exact operations involving other exact numbers—inexactness is thus contagious.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard specifies that any two implementations must produce equivalent results for all operations resulting in exact numbers.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard specifies procedures `exact->inexact` and `inexact->exact` which can be used to change the exactness of a number.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `inexact->exact` produces "the exact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `exact->inexact` produces "the inexact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard omits these procedures from the main report, but specifies them as R5RS compatibility procedures in the standard library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard, Scheme implementations are not required to implement the whole numerical tower, but they must implement "a coherent subset consistent with both the purposes of the implementation and the spirit of the Scheme language" (R5RS sec.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The new R6RS standard does require implementation of the whole tower, and "exact integer objects and exact rational number objects of practically unlimited size and precision, and to implement certain procedures...so they always return exact results when given exact arguments" (R6RS sec.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 1: exact arithmetic in an implementation that supports exact rational complex numbers.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 2: Same arithmetic in an implementation that supports neither exact rational numbers nor complex numbers but does accept real numbers in rational notation.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both implementations conform to the R5RS standard but the second does not conform to R6RS because it does not implement the full numerical tower.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme supports delayed evaluation through the `delay` form and the procedure `force`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The lexical context of the original definition of the promise is preserved, and its value is also preserved after the first use of `force`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The promise is only ever evaluated once.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These primitives, which produce or handle values known as promises, can be used to implement advanced lazy evaluation constructs such as streams.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R6RS standard, these are no longer primitives, but instead, are provided as part of the R5RS compatibility library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R5RS, a suggested implementation of `delay` and `force` is given, implementing the promise as a procedure with no arguments (a thunk) and using memoization to ensure that it is only ever evaluated once, irrespective of the number of times `force` is called (R5RS sec.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] SRFI 41 enables the expression of both finite and infinite sequences with extraordinary economy.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Lisps specify an order of evaluation for procedure arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] ev is a procedure that describes the argument passed to it, then returns the value of the argument.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast with other Lisps, the appearance of an expression in the operator position (the first item) of a Scheme expression is quite legal, as long as the result of the expression in the operator position is a procedure.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In calling the procedure "+" to add 1 and 2, the expressions (ev +), (ev 1) and (ev 2) may be evaluated in any order, as long as the effect is not as if they were evaluated in parallel.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus the following three lines may be displayed in any order by standard Scheme when the above example code is executed, although the text of one line may not be interleaved with another because that would violate the sequential evaluation constraint.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard and in later reports, the syntax of Scheme can easily be extended via the macro system.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard introduced a powerful hygienic macro system that allows the programmer to add new syntactic constructs to the language using a simple pattern matching sublanguage (R5RS sec 4.3).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to this, the hygienic macro system had been relegated to an appendix of the R4RS standard, as a "high level" system alongside a "low level" macro system, both of which were treated as extensions to Scheme rather than an essential part of the language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of the hygienic macro system, also called `syntax-rules`, are required to respect the lexical scoping of the rest of the language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is assured by special naming and scoping rules for macro expansion and avoids common programming errors that can occur in the macro systems of other programming languages.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS specifies a more sophisticated transformation system, `syntax-case`, which has been available as a language extension to R5RS Scheme for some time.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Invocations of macros and procedures bear a close resemblance—both are s-expressions—but they are treated differently.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When the compiler encounters an s-expression in the program, it first checks to see if the symbol is defined as a syntactic keyword within the current lexical scope.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If so, it then attempts to expand the macro, treating the items in the tail of the s-expression as arguments without compiling code to evaluate them, and this process is repeated recursively until no macro invocations remain.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is not a syntactic keyword, the compiler compiles code to evaluate the arguments in the tail of the s-expression and then to evaluate the variable represented by the symbol at the head of the s-expression and call it as a procedure with the evaluated tail expressions passed as arguments to it.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Scheme implementations also provide additional macro systems.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Among popular ones are syntactic closures, explicit renaming macros and `define-macro`, a non-hygienic macro system similar to `defmacro` system provided in Common Lisp.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The inability to specify whether or not a macro is hygienic is one of the shortcomings of the macro system.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alternative models for expansion such as scope sets provide a potential solution.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to R5RS, Scheme had no standard equivalent of the `eval` procedure which is ubiquitous in other Lisps, although the first Lambda Paper had described `evaluate` as "similar to the LISP function EVAL" and the first Revised Report in 1978 replaced this with `enclose`, which took two arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The second, third and fourth revised reports omitted any equivalent of `eval`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reason for this confusion is that in Scheme with its lexical scoping the result of evaluating an expression depends on where it is evaluated.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the outer environment, where `name` is defined, the result is the sum of the operands.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the inner environment, where the symbol "+" has been bound to the value of the procedure "*", the result is the product of the two operands.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS resolves this confusion by specifying three procedures that return environments and providing a procedure `eval` that takes an s-expression and an environment and evaluates the expression in the environment provided.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.5) R6RS extends this by providing a procedure called `environment` by which the programmer can specify exactly which objects to import into the evaluation environment.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `interaction-environment` is the interpreter's global environment.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In most dialects of Lisp including Common Lisp, by convention the value `NIL` evaluates to the value false in a Boolean expression.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, since the IEEE standard in 1991, all values except `#f`, including `NIL`'s equivalent in Scheme which is written as `'()`, evaluate to the value true in a Boolean expression.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Where the constant representing the Boolean value of true is `T` in most Lisps, in Scheme it is `#t`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme the primitive datatypes are disjoint.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Only one of the following predicates can be true of any Scheme object: `boolean?`, `pair?`, `symbol?`, `number?`, `char?`, `string?`, `vector?`, `port?`, `procedure?`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Within the numerical datatype, by contrast, the numerical values overlap.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, an integer value satisfies all of the `integer?`, `rational?`, `real?`, `complex?` and `number?` predicates at the same time.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Type dependent equivalence operations also exist in Scheme: `string=?` and `string-ci=?` compare two strings (the latter performs a case-independent comparison); `char=?` and `char-ci=?` compare characters; `=` compares numbers.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Up to the R5RS standard, the standard comment in Scheme was a semicolon, which makes the rest of the line invisible to Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's input and output is based on the *port* datatype.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R5RS sec 6.6) R5RS defines two default ports, accessible with the procedures `current-input-port` and `current-output-port`, which correspond to the Unix notions of standard input and standard output.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations also provide `current-error-port`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Redirection of input and standard output is supported in the standard, by standard procedures such as `with-input-from-file` and `with-output-to-file`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations provide string ports with similar redirection capabilities, enabling many normal input-output operations to be performed on string buffers instead of files, using procedures described in SRFI 6.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies much more sophisticated and capable port procedures and many new types of port.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following examples are written in strict R5RS Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 5: As 2, but with using call-with-output-file to send output to a file.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Similar procedures are provided for input.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS Scheme provides the predicates `input-port?` and `output-port?`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For character input and output, `write-char`, `read-char`, `peek-char` and `char-ready?` are provided.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For writing and reading Scheme expressions, Scheme provides `read` and `write`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] On a read operation, the result returned is the end-of-file object if the input port has reached the end of the file, and this can be tested using the predicate `eof-object?`.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] With the standard, SRFI 28 also defines a basic formatting procedure resembling Common Lisp's `format` function, after which it is named.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, procedures are bound to variables.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] At R5RS the language standard formally mandated that programs may change the variable bindings of built-in procedures, effectively redefining them.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS every binding, including the standard ones, belongs to some library, and all exported bindings are immutable.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R6RS sec 7.1) Because of this, redefinition of standard procedures by mutation is forbidden.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Instead, it is possible to import a different procedure under the name of a standard one, which in effect is similar to redefinition.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Standard Scheme, procedures that convert from one datatype to another contain the character string "->" in their name, predicates end with a "?", and procedures that change the value of already-allocated data end with a "!".
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These conventions are often followed by Scheme programmers.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In formal contexts such as Scheme standards, the word "procedure" is used in preference to "function" to refer to a lambda expression or primitive procedure.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In normal usage, the words "procedure" and "function" are used interchangeably.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Procedure application is sometimes referred to formally as *combination*.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] As in other Lisps, the term "thunk" is used in Scheme to refer to a procedure with no arguments.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The term "proper tail recursion" refers to the property of all Scheme implementations, that they perform tail-call optimization so as to support an indefinite number of active tail calls.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The language is formally defined in the standards R5RS (1998), R6RS (2007), and R7RS (2013).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They describe standard "forms": keywords and accompanying syntax, which provide the control structure of the language, and standard procedures which perform common tasks.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This table describes the standard forms in Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some forms appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Forms marked "L" in this table are classed as derived "library" forms in the standard and are often implemented as macros using more fundamental forms in practice, making the task of implementation much easier than in other languages.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] While `begin` is defined as a library syntax in R5RS, the expander must know about it to achieve the splicing function.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS it is no longer a library syntax.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following two tables describe the standard procedures in R5RS Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS is far more extensive and a summary of this type would not be practical.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some procedures appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] String and character procedures that contain "-ci" in their names perform case-independent comparisons between their arguments: upper case and lower case versions of the same character are taken to be equal.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of - and / that take more than two arguments are defined but left optional at R5RS.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Because of Scheme's minimalism, many common procedures and syntactic forms are not defined by the standard.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In order to keep the core language small but facilitate standardization of extensions, the Scheme community has a "Scheme Request for Implementation" (SRFI) process by which extension libraries are defined through careful discussion of extension proposals.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many of the SRFIs are supported by all or most Scheme implementations.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The elegant, minimalist design has made Scheme a popular target for language designers, hobbyists, and educators, and because of its small size, that of a typical interpreter, it is also a popular choice for embedded systems and scripting.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies a much broader language, in an attempt to broaden its appeal to programmers.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Almost all implementations provide a traditional Lisp-style read–eval–print loop for development and debugging.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many also compile Scheme programs to executable binary.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Support for embedding Scheme code in programs written in other languages is also common, as the relative simplicity of Scheme implementations makes it a popular choice for adding scripting capabilities to larger systems developed in languages such as C.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Gambit, Chicken, and Bigloo Scheme interpreters compile Scheme to C, which makes embedding far easier.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Further, Bigloo's compiler can be configured to generate bytecode for the Java virtual machine (JVM), and has an experimental bytecode generator for .NET.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some implementations support added features.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, Kawa and JScheme provide integration with Java classes, and the Scheme to C compilers often make it easy to use external libraries written in C, up to allowing the embedding of C code in the Scheme source code.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Another example is Pvts, which offers a set of visual tools that support Scheme learning.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is widely used by several schools; in particular, several introductory computer science courses use Scheme in conjunction with the textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* (SICP).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For the past 12 years, PLT has run the ProgramByDesign (formerly TeachScheme!) project, which has exposed close to 600 high school teachers and thousands of high school students to rudimentary Scheme programming.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] MIT's old introductory programming class 6.001 was taught in Scheme, Although 6.001 has been replaced by more modern courses, SICP continues to be taught at MIT.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Likewise, the introductory class at UC Berkeley, CS 61A, was until 2011 taught entirely in Scheme, save minor diversions into Logo to demonstrate dynamic scope.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Today, like MIT, Berkeley has replaced the syllabus with a more modern version that is primarily taught in Python 3, but the current syllabus is still based on the old curriculum, and parts of the class are still taught in Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The textbook *How to Design Programs* is used by some institutes of higher education for their introductory computer science courses.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Worcester Polytechnic Institute uses Scheme exclusively for its introductory course Introduction to Program Design (CS1101).
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology uses Scheme in its more advanced Programming Language Concepts course.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Brandeis University's core course, Structure and Interpretations of Computer Programs (COSI121b), is also taught exclusively in Scheme by theoretical computer scientist Harry Mairson.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Indiana University's introductory class, C211, is taught entirely in Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A self-paced version of the course, CS 61AS, continues to use Scheme.
[src:guile-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introductory computer science courses at Yale and Grinnell College are also taught in Scheme.
